>European chocolate 
>Cadbury 
I mean, seriously? Among all amazing chocolates from European countries known for their chocolate skills like Belgium or Switzerland you chose this sweet-ass Cadbury? ;-;

I can't stand Us choco. Cadbury tastes horrible too, a harsh, overly sweet, with sour/bitter undertones, which explains why I wouldn't I wouldn't buy Milka products for the longest time, just because both are purple & I mixed up the 2. Although I have learned from the comments that both are owned by the same company, Milka actually has a European chocolate taste, soft, mellow & buttery, they are the biggest sellers on the market because they have a middle ground taste that works for teenagers & adults. To compare to other brands well known in Europe: 
Kinder, geared for kids, goes heavier on the sugar, while Ferrero & Raffaello, same company but marketed to adults, try to strike the perfect balance with the nuts or coco, & everyone knows Nutella;
Lindt: what I call indulgence chocolat, extra soft & creamy;
Mars, Twix, Toblerone, etc: the too sweet, but still tasty in half/quarter doses, from time to time, & a lot better tasting in ice cream;
The store brand: the cheapest, watered down, but still decent tasting option for lighter wallets;
Then you have to add all the specialized chocolate brands, like Jeff de Bruges, more expensive, but also more refined & with more variety, they usually have their own small shops.
Edit: Adding Ritter Sport, mostly unknown in France, but decent basic chocolat.

